Celebriouly accompliht as Dorame was, would he from the time that her dear Cliidas expired have entertained propoals of a econd Husband, he might have had the ame day of his Funerals, to have been that alo of her Nuptials. More than a few of the higher rank ought her in Mariage, and
• his her new Paionate was not ignorant of;
but there was no body whom he feared but her whom he loved, and nothing that he cared for but to make her love him. But before that he by any uites or declarations to her delivered his mind of that with which it was big, he thought it bet often to viit her, and every time that he viited her, as he found in her Wit, Humour, Fahion, Form, ome new occaion of admiring her and of coveting her with impatience for his Wife, o the generounes and weetnes of his dipoition, the equability and moderation of his temper, the Elegancy and ublimenes of his Ingenij, the gracefulnes of his Peron and carriage, and the great Civility or rather Devotion of his repectfulnes to her, more and more nouriht and augmented that kind eteem which from her firt knowledge of him he had conceived for him, o that before it was long, if he had at any time any thoughts of being re-married, it was only to Alcidor, that which would have made him account himelf a mot happy Man had he been acquainted with it, but he very watchfully concealed it from him.
